Sure! Here's an example of how to generate a table of contents automatically in a LATEX document:

First, you'll need to add the necessary packages to your document. In this case, we'll use the `tableofcontents` package:
```
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tableofcontents}
```
Next, you'll need to add the `\tableofcontents` command to your document. This command should be placed after the document's introduction, but before the first section:
```
\begin{document}

\tableofcontents

\section{Introduction}
\label{introduction}

This is the introduction to the document.

\section{Section 1}
\label{section1}

This is the first section of the document.

\section{Section 2}
\label{section2}

This is the second section of the document.

\section{Section 3}
\label{section3}

This is the third section of the document.

\end{document}
```
When you compile this document, LATEX will generate a table of contents based on the section headings in the document. The table of contents will be placed after the introduction, but before the first section.

You can customize the appearance of the table of contents by adding additional options to the `\tableofcontents` command. For example, you can change the font size, font style, and colors used in the table of contents by adding the following options:
```
\tableofcontents[font=\footnotesize,heading=section,color=blue]
```
This will change the font size to footnotesize, set the heading level to section, and change the color of the table of contents to blue.

You can also add additional items to the table of contents using the `addcontentsline` command. For example, to add a list of figures or a list of tables to the table of contents, you can use the following commands:
```
\addcontentsline{toc}{part}{List of Figures}
\addcontentsline{toc}{part}{List of Tables}
```
These commands will add a new part to the table of contents with the specified label, and list the labels of the figures or tables included in that part.

