To draw a chessboard in LATEX, you can use the `tikz` package and its built-in `chessboard` command.

Here's an example of how you can use the `chessboard` command to draw a chessboard in LATEX:
```
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usetikzlibrary{chessboard}

\begin{document}

\begin{tikzpicture}
\chessboard{8}{8}
\end{tikzpicture}

\end{document}
```
This will produce a square chessboard with 8x8 squares. You can adjust the size of the board by changing the arguments passed to the `chessboard` command. For example, to create a 6x6 board, you can use `\chessboard{6}{6}`.

If you want to customize the appearance of the board, you can use various options provided by the `chessboard` command. For example, you can change the color of the squares using the `square_size` option, or add borders to the board using the `border` option.

Here's an example of how you can customize the appearance of the board:
```
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usetikzlibrary{chessboard}

\begin{document}

\begin{tikzpicture}
\chessboard[square_size=2cm,border=1pt]{8}{8}
\end{tikzpicture}

\end{document}
```
This will produce a board with 2cm square size and 1pt border.

If you want to add FEN notation to the board, you can use the `fen` package and its `fen` environment. Here's an example of how you can use the `fen` environment to add FEN notation to the board:
```
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usetikzlibrary{chessboard}
\usepackage{fen}

\begin{document}

\begin{tikzpicture}
